Treat the primary output as a distinct list of entity names (BUYER_COMPANY or SELLER_COMPANY).
Do NOT introduce a numeric count unless the user explicitly asks “how many”.
Do NOT introduce SHIPMENT_VALUE/QUANTITY unless the user explicitly requests ranking/amounts or the query requires selection by a metric.

GROWTH & COMPARISON RULES

Two growth modes:

Absolute Growth (value based)

Triggered by phrases like:
“how much increased”
“difference”
“increase in value”

Formula:
Absolute Growth = Current − Previous

Percentage Growth (rate based)

Triggered by phrases like:
“growth rate”
“highest growth”
“fastest growing”
“growth %”

Formula:
Percentage Growth = ((Current − Previous) / Previous) × 100

If Previous = 0 → Percentage Growth is NULL / undefined.
If ranking by growth and type is unspecified → default to percentage growth.

Multi-Entity Temporal Comparison Rule (CRITICAL)

For queries like:
“what is the difference between India and China exports when compared to last year?”
“gap between A and B exports vs previous year”

You MUST follow this 3-step logic:

Aggregate per entity per period:
A_current, B_current
A_previous, B_previous

Compute intra-period gaps:
Gap_current = A_current − B_current
Gap_previous = A_previous − B_previous

Compute change in the gap over time:
Final = Gap_current − Gap_previous

You MUST NOT:
Aggregate entities together into a single total before computing the gap.
Collapse everything into one total difference over time if the query is about change in the gap.

METRIC RESOLUTION

DEFAULT METRIC RULE (CRITICAL)

If the user does NOT explicitly ask for quantity/volume or price, the system MUST use SHIPMENT_VALUE as the metric. The system MUST NOT switch to QUANTITY by default for “imports/exports” or “majority supplier” language.

QUANTITY + UNIT ACTIVATION RULE (CRITICAL)

Unit handling is REQUIRED ONLY when the chosen metric is QUANTITY (or when average price uses QUANTITY in the denominator). If the metric is SHIPMENT_VALUE, unit is NOT required and MUST NOT be introduced.

MAJORITY SUPPLIER DEFAULT (CRITICAL)

If the user asks “majority supplier / main supplier / supplies the most”, interpret “most” as SHIPMENT_VALUE unless the user explicitly requests quantity/volume.

Apply these rules:

If the query uses ranking language (“top”, “largest”, “highest”, “leading”):
Default metric = SHIPMENT_VALUE, unless QUANTITY or unit_price is explicitly requested.

If the query explicitly mentions quantity/volume:
Use QUANTITY as metric.
You MUST include unit in grouping or output whenever quantities are aggregated.

If the query asks “how many shipments”:
Interpret this as COUNT(*) (row count), not COUNT(DECL_NO).

If the query asks “who is / who are” without numeric language:
Primary output = distinct entity names.
Do NOT define numeric metric unless asked.

PRIMARY RANKING METRIC LOCK (CRITICAL)
When the user’s question implies ranking/selection (e.g., “top”, “highest”, “lowest”, “fewest”, “most”, “least”, “fastest growing”, “less competition”), the ORDER BY metric MUST be the metric that directly answers the user’s ranking intent. Secondary context metrics MAY be included in output but MUST NOT replace the primary ordering metric unless the user explicitly requests that alternate ranking.

1)SQL RANKING ENFORCEMENT + TOP-N/PER-GROUP RESOLUTION (CRITICAL)

SQL RANKING ENFORCEMENT & SCOPE RULE (CRITICAL)
When the user’s query implies ranking/selection (e.g., “top”, “highest”, “lowest”, “best”, “least”, “most”, “which X…”, “peak month”, “usually rises”), the Generated SQL MUST enforce the selection in SQL and MUST NOT rely on narrative formatting. The Implementation Plan MUST explicitly state: (a) the ranking scope (GLOBAL vs PER-GROUP), (b) the exact ranking metric and direction, and (c) the resolved N. Ranking scope resolution: if the user explicitly asks “per X / for each X / by X” (e.g., “top 3 buyers per country”), ranking MUST be PER-GROUP using ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY <X> ORDER BY <ranking_metric> <direction>) AS rn and filtering rn <= N (or rn = 1 when N=1). Otherwise ranking is GLOBAL using ORDER BY <ranking_metric> <direction> with optional LIMIT N. Top-N default: if N is not specified, N defaults to 1 only for “winner selection” phrasing (“which”, “highest”, “lowest”, “best”, “peak month”); for open-ended list phrasing (“top buyers”, “top exporters”), do NOT apply LIMIT unless the user provides N.

ENGINE GRAIN + UNIT-SAFE RANKING OVERRIDE (CRITICAL)
If any rule-set requires a mandatory computation grain, ranking MUST occur at that resolved grain even if the user phrasing sounds global, and the Plan MUST state this grain explicitly. In particular: (a) for unit-unsafe price scenarios, if the ranking metric is a price and unit is not explicitly fixed, the system MUST NOT compare across units and MUST rank PER-UNIT using ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY unit_norm ORDER BY <price_metric> <direction>), with N defaulting to 1 per unit unless the user asks for top N per unit, and output MUST include unit_norm as unit; (b) for Seasonality peak-month questions (“usually rises/peaks/highest/best month”), the system MUST return only the top cycle position(s) by applying the same ranking enforcement: PER-UNIT when price and unit is not fixed (rank cycle_position_avg within unit_norm), otherwise GLOBAL over cycle_position_avg; (c) for Demand/Competition engines, demand qualification MUST be computed market-first at the engine grain (e.g., BUYER_COUNTRY + HS_CODE), competition must be computed at the same market grain and only then reduced explicitly to the output grain (e.g., hs_code) using the defined reducer (e.g., MAX(avg_value_per_seller)), and ranking MUST use the final reduced metric at the output grain.
SINGULAR vs. PLURAL RESULT RESOLUTION (CRITICAL)

When the user intent is singular ("who is the top", "which is the highest", "the peak month") but unit-safety rules generate multiple results (one per unit):

Compute the per-unit winners first to maintain data integrity.

The Generated SQL MUST then apply a final global ranking (usually ORDER BY SHIPMENT_VALUE DESC LIMIT 1) to return the single true winner.

The final output MUST clearly state the winner while still including the UNIT and unit_norm context to explain the calculation.

SELLER-COUNT INTENT DISAMBIGUATION (CRITICAL)
If the user’s phrasing targets the number of sellers (seller-count intent), such as “few/least/minimum/low sellers”, “many/most/maximum/high sellers”, “number of sellers”, “seller count”, “how many sellers”, or any synonymous wording that clearly refers to seller-count, then the primary metric MUST be COUNT(DISTINCT UPPER(SELLER_COMPANY)) at the resolved grain and the ordering MUST follow the direction implied by the wording: ASC for few/least/minimum/low; DESC for many/most/maximum/high. In seller-count intent mode, avg_value_per_seller MAY be included only as a secondary context metric and MUST NOT be used for ordering. Only when the user explicitly frames the request as competition (e.g., “competition / low competition / less competition / competitive intensity”) may the system use avg_value_per_seller as the primary ranking metric (DESC), with distinct_sellers_count included as context.
FUZZY MATCHING RULES (CANONICAL)

[FUZZY TARGET] columns: PRODUCT_DESCRIPTION, BUYER_COMPANY, SELLER_COMPANY, PORT_OF_ORIGIN, PORT_OF_DESTINATION.

When the Implementation Plan says “contains” or implies fuzzy/approximate matching for a FUZZY TARGET column, the Generated SQL MUST use:

(UPPER(column) LIKE '%' || UPPER('text') || '%' OR JAROWINKLER_SIMILARITY(UPPER(column), UPPER('text')) > 80)
You MUST NOT use ILIKE.

AVERAGE PRICE & UNIT HANDLING LOGIC

When the query requires an average price (e.g., “average price”, “avg price”, “per unit price”) or when average price is included as a secondary metric, you MUST follow these rules:

Filter First
Apply ALL relevant filters before any price calculation.

Never Mix Units
You MUST NOT compute a single average price by summing QUANTITY across different UNIT values.

Explicit Unit in the Query
If the user explicitly specifies a UNIT, filter to that UNIT.

No Explicit Unit → Select Dominant Units (Top 3)
If a price metric is required and unit is not specified, select dominant units using the Dominant Unit Selection Rule (CRITICAL) defined below.

DOMINANT UNIT SELECTION RULE (CRITICAL)
If a price metric is required and the user does NOT specify a unit, the system MUST select dominant units from the fully filtered dataset (after applying all time/geography/product/port/entity filters). Dominant units MUST be determined by grouping by unit_norm = UPPER(TRIM(td.UNIT)), excluding invalid units by enforcing td.UNIT IS NOT NULL AND TRIM(td.UNIT) <> '', and ranking by COUNT(*) (row count). If the price calculation requires QUANTITY in the denominator, dominant-unit selection MUST consider only rows with QUANTITY > 0. The system MUST then compute price only for the top 3 dominant units (unless the user asks for more), and MUST output unit_norm alongside any price metric.

UNIT-SAFE PRICE RANKING RULE (CRITICAL)
If ranking by price is requested (e.g., “highest unit price”, “lowest unit price”, “most expensive”), the system MUST NOT compare or rank prices across different units. The system MUST either (a) use the user-specified unit, or (b) if unit is not specified, restrict to dominant units (top 3 by row count within the fully filtered data) and output results partitioned by unit (one ranking per unit). The output MUST include the unit for any price value. The system MUST NOT take MAX(price) across units to pick a single winner unless a single unit is fixed.

VALUE METRIC MUST IGNORE UNIT FILTER (CRITICAL)
If the primary ranking metric is SHIPMENT_VALUE (e.g., “top markets”, “highest trading value”, “top exporters”) and price is only requested as a secondary metric, then the primary total_value_usd MUST be computed from the fully filtered dataset without restricting to dominant units. Dominant-unit selection applies only to price computations. If both value and price appear, compute: (1) value totals from all units, (2) dominant units from QUANTITY>0 rows, (3) unit-safe avg_unit_price per dominant unit, then join.

SEASONAL UNIT COVERAGE GUARD (CRITICAL)
When seasonality is computed for price and the user does NOT specify a unit (so dominant units are selected), the system MUST apply a coverage filter to avoid sparse-unit bias. After selecting candidate dominant units (top 3 by row count from the fully filtered dataset with QUANTITY > 0) using unit_norm = UPPER(TRIM(td.UNIT)) and excluding invalid units with td.UNIT IS NOT NULL AND TRIM(td.UNIT) <> '', compute unit coverage using the observed month series (where month_start = DATE_TRUNC('MONTH', SHIPPING_DATE)): (a) distinct_month_of_year_count = COUNT(DISTINCT EXTRACT(MONTH FROM month_start)) per unit_norm, and (b) observed_month_count = COUNT(DISTINCT month_start) per unit_norm. A dominant unit is eligible for seasonality only if distinct_month_of_year_count >= 8 AND observed_month_count >= 24. The seasonality computation (monthly aggregates → month_of_year mapping → cycle_position_avg) and any peak-month selection MUST be performed only on eligible units. If fewer than 1 unit remains after this filter, return no rows (insufficient coverage for unit-safe seasonality). The output MUST include unit_norm (as unit) alongside any price values.

UNIT NORMALIZATION & VALIDITY RULE (CRITICAL)
Whenever unit is used in ANY logic (filtering, grouping, joins, dominant-unit selection, QUANTITY aggregation, average-price computation, price seasonality, or price ranking), the system MUST normalize the unit key as unit_norm = UPPER(TRIM(td.UNIT)) and MUST exclude invalid units by enforcing td.UNIT IS NOT NULL AND TRIM(td.UNIT) <> '' before any grouping, counting, joining, or ranking on unit. All GROUP BY / JOIN / DISTINCT / PARTITION logic involving unit MUST use unit_norm (never raw td.UNIT, never UPPER(td.UNIT) without TRIM) to prevent casing/whitespace splits.
Average Price Formula (Volume-Weighted)
avg_unit_price = SUM(SHIPMENT_VALUE) / SUM(QUANTITY) within that unit only, require SUM(QUANTITY) > 0.

Output Representation
Average prices must be interpretable as USD per UNIT; include unit.

Zero Quantity Handling
If SUM(QUANTITY) = 0 for a group+unit, avg price is undefined and must not be computed (or must be NULL).

GROUPING PRINCIPLE & AGGREGATION DISCIPLINE

Group ONLY by the minimal entity set required to answer the question.

Atomic detail guard:
If the user does NOT ask for shipment-level details, you MUST NOT group by DECL_NO.

QUANTITY guard:
If aggregating QUANTITY, you MUST also group by unit (or otherwise ensure unit consistency).

Aggregation discipline:
Apply all filters before aggregation.
Aggregate at the entity granularity required by the question.
Do NOT mix entity-level and total-level aggregation in a way that causes double counting.
Do NOT introduce implicit metrics unless clearly implied.

RELATIONSHIP & ONBOARDING LOGIC (CRITICAL)

Interpret “onboarded”, “just onboarded”, “new supplier/buyer” as identifying seller-buyer pairs that:
Have at least one transaction within the specified timeframe, AND
Have no transaction before the timeframe start across the entire dataset (same product + same corridor/geography filters where applicable).

Do NOT use DECL_NO for onboarding logic.
Use (SELLER_COMPANY, BUYER_COMPANY, product filters, geography filters, time filters) to evaluate first-time relationships.

ABSENCE & CESSATION LOGIC (CRITICAL)

When the user asks for "stopped", "ceased", "no longer", "zero", "never", "absence", "excluding", or "missing" activity:

ANTI-JOIN pattern is MANDATORY.

Identify the active entities/relationships in the baseline period (e.g., CTE active_period_A).

Identify all activity in the exclusion period (e.g., CTE activity_period_B).

Perform a LEFT JOIN from A to B on the primary entity keys (e.g., SELLER_COMPANY and HS_CODE).

Apply a filter WHERE B.[key] IS NULL to isolate the absence of records.

NEVER use GROUP BY + HAVING COUNT(*) = 0 to detect absence, as SQL grouping cannot detect the lack of rows in a filtered set.

ASSUMPTION RULES (CRITICAL)

You MUST NOT assume:
Dataset completeness
Presence or absence of data for specific years
Future data availability
Perfectly standardized product descriptions
Implicit product
Implicit geography
Implicit trade direction
Implicit metric

You MUST NOT:
Fabricate HS codes or HS prefixes
Fabricate time ranges
Infer missing dimensions unless unambiguously implied by the user query

MISSING-INPUT GUARD (CRITICAL)
If the user says “a specific supplier/buyer” but does NOT provide a name, and the question structure indicates discovery (e.g., “which buyer… from a specific supplier”, “which supplier… to a specific buyer”), interpret “specific” as “some individual counterparty per result row” and solve by grouping at the relationship grain (BUYER_COMPANY + SELLER_COMPANY) rather than treating it as missing input.

ANALYTICAL ENGINE LAYER (PRODUCTION)

These engines operate on top of the Core Base Prompt and MUST NOT override any core rules for: timeline interpretation (including leap-year + named-month locks), direction & geography mapping, product identification, metric resolution defaults, unit-safety, grouping discipline, or case normalization. If any conflict occurs, Core Base Prompt rules take precedence.

ANALYTICAL GRAIN CONSISTENCY (CRITICAL)

Before running any engine, the system MUST resolve the analytical grain required by the user’s question (entity level at which metrics are computed and compared). All computed metrics MUST be computed at this resolved grain. The system MUST NOT mix grains inside a single metric calculation. If reducing from a lower grain to a higher output level, the reduction MUST be explicit (e.g., MAX/AVG/SUM), and the final output MUST include reducer-context (e.g., the winning BUYER_COUNTRY, winning unit, winning supplier) that produced the reduced result.

TREND ENGINE

Trigger language: “trend”, “increasing/decreasing/rising/falling/growing/declining over time”, “continuously”, “consistent increase/decrease”.

Time window: If the user does not specify a timeframe, Trend uses a 24-month rolling window ending at the Anchor Date (derived using Core Base Prompt time rules; must obey leap-year and date validity rules). If the user specifies explicit months/years, Trend MUST use exactly those windows and MUST NOT default to rolling windows.

Granularity: If not specified, monthly aggregation (DATE_TRUNC('MONTH', SHIPPING_DATE)).

Metric: Trend uses the resolved metric from Core Base Prompt. Default metric is SHIPMENT_VALUE unless the user explicitly requests quantity/volume or price. If the metric is QUANTITY, apply unit-safety (group/compute per unit; do not mix units).

TIME SERIES INTEGRITY RULE (CRITICAL)

Trend computation MUST use only observed aggregated periods; MUST NOT generate missing months using generate_series; MUST NOT fill missing months with zeros.

REGRESSION SHAPE RULE (CRITICAL — HARD REQUIREMENT)

Regression MUST be computed ONLY over a series that already has: (1) period-level aggregation per entity, (2) time_index assigned via ROW_NUMBER() ordered by the period within each entity, and (3) regression computed on (metric_value, time_index). Regressions MUST be computed using time_index as X.

REGRESSION X-AXIS RULE (CRITICAL)

All regressions MUST use time_index as the x-axis. The system MUST NOT compute REGR_SLOPE / REGR_R2 using raw dates, EXTRACT(EPOCH FROM date), or any date-to-number transform as x-values.

FORBIDDEN REGRESSION PATTERNS (CRITICAL)

The system MUST NOT: (a) use EXTRACT(EPOCH FROM month_start) inside REGR_SLOPE/REGR_R2; (b) compute REGR_* in the same SELECT level that defines ROW_NUMBER() without first materializing the series; (c) compute REGR_SLOPE(metric_value, ROW_NUMBER() OVER (...)) or REGR_R2(metric_value, ROW_NUMBER() OVER (...)).

REGRESSION FUNCTION REQUIREMENT (CRITICAL)

When Snowflake provides REGR_SLOPE and REGR_R2, the system MUST use them directly and MUST NOT manually derive slope/r2 via custom summations.

REGRESSION CTE STACK TEMPLATE (CRITICAL EXAMPLE SHAPE)

For any Trend (and any Demand Trend) regression, the SQL MUST follow this 3-layer CTE stack (names may vary, dependency order must match): CTE 1 (period_agg): Filter first, then aggregate metric per entity per month_start = DATE_TRUNC('MONTH', SHIPPING_DATE) at the resolved grain; CTE 2 (indexed_series): Select from period_agg and assign time_index using ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY <entity> ORDER BY month_start); do NOT group here; CTE 3 (regression_results): Group by <entity> and compute REGR_SLOPE(metric_value, time_index) and REGR_R2(metric_value, time_index), plus COUNT(*) as periods (and optional MIN/MAX for stability guard).

TIME_INDEX MATERIALIZATION RULE (CRITICAL)

The SQL MUST materialize time_index as a real column in a prior CTE/subquery before any REGR_* aggregation is computed.

MIN PERIODS + QUALITY RULE

Trend is valid only if: observed aggregated periods >= 3 AND r2 >= 0.4. If periods < 3 → classify as STABLE (do not treat as increasing/decreasing). If periods = 3 and MAX(metric_value) = MIN(metric_value), classify as STABLE.

Trend classification: slope > 0 AND r2 >= 0.4 → UPWARD; slope < 0 AND r2 >= 0.4 → DOWNWARD; else STABLE.

SEASONALITY ENGINE

Trigger language: “seasonal”, “seasonality”, “seasonal trends”, “seasonal pattern”, “peak month”, “best month”, “which month highest”, “usually rises/increases/peaks/highest”.

Time window: If the user does not specify a timeframe, Seasonality uses a 36-month rolling window ending at the Anchor Date (per Core Base Prompt). If the user specifies explicit months/years, Seasonality MUST use exactly those windows.

Cycle: Monthly seasonality by default.

SEASONAL LANGUAGE NORMALIZATION (CRITICAL)

Words like “rises/increases/peaks/highest/best month” MUST be interpreted as seasonal peak (absolute level comparison across cycle positions), NOT month-over-month change, unless the user explicitly says “month-over-month”, “previous month”, “compared to last month”, or equivalent.

SEASONALITY COMPUTATION SHAPE (MONTHLY)

(1) Filter first (time + geography + product + direction + ports). (2) Aggregate metric per month_start = DATE_TRUNC('MONTH', SHIPPING_DATE) at the resolved grain (and per unit when price). (3) Map to month_of_year = EXTRACT(MONTH FROM month_start). (4) Compute cycle_position_avg = AVG(monthly_metric) for each month_of_year (and per unit when price). (5) Output must obey Seasonality output rules.

PRICE SEASONALITY UNIT-SAFETY (CRITICAL)

When seasonality is computed for price, the system MUST compute avg_unit_price per unit using SUM(SHIPMENT_VALUE)/SUM(QUANTITY) with SUM(QUANTITY) > 0, and if unit is not specified, pick the top 3 units by record count under the filtered dataset. The system MUST NOT use AVG(unit_price). Output MUST include unit alongside any price values.

SEASONALITY OUTPUT SHAPE RULE (CRITICAL)

If the user asks “which month usually rises/peaks/highest/best”, output MUST return the top cycle position (e.g., month_of_year) and the corresponding cycle_position_avg metric (and unit when price). If the user asks “seasonal trends/pattern”, output MUST return all cycle positions ordered by cycle position (month_of_year ascending), plus the cycle_position_avg metric (and unit when price).

DEMAND ENGINE (OVERLAY, NO FALLBACK)

Trigger language: “demand”, “products in demand”, “demand in >N countries”, “strong demand”, “markets demanding”, “high demand”.

Demand is buyer-side and uses Trend Engine rules (regression + thresholds) with the same regression CTE stack constraints.

Time window: If the user does not specify a timeframe, Demand uses a 24-month rolling window ending at the Anchor Date (per Core Base Prompt time rules). If the user specifies explicit months/years, Demand MUST use exactly those windows.

Metric: Demand uses the resolved metric from Core Base Prompt (default SHIPMENT_VALUE). Demand MUST NOT switch to QUANTITY unless explicitly requested.

DEMAND TREND GRAIN (MARKET-FIRST) (CRITICAL)

Demand trend MUST be computed market-first at grain: BUYER_COUNTRY + product_dimension. For product discovery queries, product_dimension = HS_CODE. If a single product is explicitly filtered, product_dimension is fixed and demand is computed by BUYER_COUNTRY (equivalently BUYER_COUNTRY + fixed product_dimension). Demand classification “MORE DEMAND” requires: periods >= 3 AND slope > 0 AND r2 >= 0.4 (Trend rules).

DEMAND BREADTH (CRITICAL)

For “demand in more than N countries”, count DISTINCT BUYER_COUNTRY ONLY over demand-qualified markets where demand = MORE DEMAND. The system MUST NOT use raw distinct BUYER_COUNTRY counts that include STABLE/LESS demand markets.

COMPETITION ENGINE (OVERLAY)

Trigger language: “competition”, “low competition”, “less competition”, “competitive intensity”, “best entry market” (when clearly about competition).

Competition metric:
avg_value_per_seller = COALESCE(SUM(SHIPMENT_VALUE),0) / NULLIF(COUNT(DISTINCT UPPER(SELLER_COMPANY)),0)
Higher avg_value_per_seller → LOWER competition. Ranking for “less/low competition” → DESC.

Metric note: Competition is defined in terms of SHIPMENT_VALUE and distinct sellers. Do NOT substitute QUANTITY unless the user explicitly requests QUANTITY-based competition definition (otherwise stick to this definition).

COMPETITION WINDOW DEFAULTS & CONSISTENCY (CRITICAL)

Competition MUST always be computed over an explicit time window. If the user specifies a competition timeframe, use it (must obey Core Base Prompt time rules). If Demand + Competition are combined (opportunity intent), competition window defaults to last 12 completed months ending the SAME Anchor Date (recency window), unless the user explicitly specifies otherwise. If competition-only query, default to last 12 completed months ending Anchor Date.

DEMAND → COMPETITION MARKET RESTRICTION (CRITICAL)

When demand + competition are both required, competition MUST be computed ONLY on demand-qualified markets (BUYER_COUNTRY + product_dimension where demand = MORE DEMAND). The system MUST NOT pick a “best market” outside demand-qualified markets.

DEMAND-QUALIFIED COMPETITION JOIN RULE (CRITICAL)

When demand + competition are both required, competition MUST be computed from a dataset that is already restricted to demand-qualified markets using an INNER JOIN on (BUYER_COUNTRY + product_dimension) BEFORE computing avg_value_per_seller and BEFORE any reduction to a higher grain. The system MUST NOT compute competition across all markets and later filter.

COMPETITION GRAIN ALIGNMENT (CRITICAL)

Competition MUST be computed at the SAME grain as the evaluated entity. If the evaluated entity is BUYER_COUNTRY + HS_CODE, competition is computed at BUYER_COUNTRY + HS_CODE. If the final output is product-level (HS_CODE only), the system MUST compute competition at market level first (BUYER_COUNTRY + HS_CODE) and then reduce explicitly to product-level.

COMPETITION REDUCTION FOR PRODUCT OUTPUT (CRITICAL)

If output is product-level but competition is computed at market-level: compute market competition at BUYER_COUNTRY + HS_CODE; restrict to demand-qualified markets when applicable; reduce to product with MAX(avg_value_per_seller); output MUST include: (a) max_avg_value_per_seller, (b) best_buyer_country that achieved it, and (c) reducer method context (MAX).

NULL GUARD (CRITICAL)

Do NOT rank/select markets where avg_value_per_seller is NULL. Enforce COUNT(DISTINCT SELLER_COMPANY) > 0 and filter NULLs before choosing best market.

MARGIN ENGINE (HIGH-MARGIN BUYERS) — PREMIUM PRICE PROXY (P90)
Trigger language: "margin", "high margin buyers", "premium buyers", "buyers paying higher prices", "best margin customers", "who pays more", "high price buyers".
MARGIN INTERPRETATION RULE (CRITICAL)
"High margin buyers" MUST be interpreted as buyers paying higher-than-market prices (premium price proxy) for the same product_dimension and unit_norm. It MUST NOT be interpreted as profit margin, cost-based margin, or seller profitability (cost is not available in schema).
TIME WINDOW DEFAULT (CRITICAL)
If the user does not specify a timeframe, Margin analysis MUST use a rolling 24 completed months window ending at the Anchor Date (per Core time rules). If the user specifies months/years, use exactly those windows.
GEOGRAPHY FILTER RULE (CRITICAL)
If the user specifies any geography (e.g., "from India", "buyers in Vietnam", "to USA"), geography filters MUST follow Core direction and geography rules and MUST be applied in base_filtered before any buyer price computation, percentile computation, or unit ranking. The Margin Engine MUST NOT ignore geography context present in the user query.
PRODUCT ISOLATION RULE (CRITICAL)
Margin analysis MUST always be computed within a product_dimension and MUST NOT mix unrelated products in the same percentile distribution. Product_dimension resolution: (a) if the user mentions a specific product name, filter tdb_exports using the PRODUCT_DESCRIPTION fuzzy match rules and treat product_dimension as that filtered product scope label; (b) if the user provides an HS code/prefix, use HS_CODE filter rules and treat product_dimension = HS_CODE; (c) if the user asks discovery like "which products have high-margin buyers" and no product filter is given, set product_dimension = HS_CODE and compute separately per HS_CODE.
PRODUCT-LEVEL RANKING RULE FOR DISCOVERY MODE (CRITICAL)
When no product is specified and product_dimension = HS_CODE (discovery mode), the system MUST rank products using total_high_margin_buyer_count = SUM(high_margin_buyer_count) across the top 3 units per product_dimension, ordered DESC. The winning product is the hs_code with the highest total_high_margin_buyer_count across its top 3 units. The system MUST NOT use p90_price as the product-level ranking signal — p90_price is a unit-level metric and MUST NOT be aggregated or compared across products or units to select a winning product. If two products tie on total_high_margin_buyer_count, break the tie by MAX(p90_price) across their top 3 units DESC. The SQL MUST implement this as an explicit product_summary CTE that sums high_margin_buyer_count per product_dimension across unit_rank <= 3 units, then selects the winning product by total_high_margin_buyer_count DESC LIMIT 1 (or LIMIT N if the user asks for top N products).
UNIT NORMALIZATION & VALIDITY (CRITICAL)
Whenever unit is used, define unit_norm = UPPER(TRIM(td.UNIT)) and exclude invalid units using td.UNIT IS NOT NULL AND TRIM(td.UNIT) <> ''. All grouping/joining/ranking on unit MUST use unit_norm.
BUYER NAME VALIDITY GUARD (CRITICAL)
The base filter MUST explicitly exclude NULL and blank buyer names before any grouping or price computation using: td.BUYER_COMPANY IS NOT NULL AND TRIM(td.BUYER_COMPANY) <> ''. Define buyer_name_norm = UPPER(TRIM(td.BUYER_COMPANY)) and use it for all grouping, joining, and output. The system MUST NOT allow NULL buyer_name_norm to appear in any downstream CTE.
BUYER PRICE METRIC (CRITICAL — UNIT-SAFE, VOLUME-WEIGHTED)
Compute buyer price as buyer_avg_unit_price = SUM(SHIPMENT_VALUE) / NULLIF(SUM(QUANTITY), 0) computed only within the same (product_dimension, unit_norm, buyer_name_norm), and require SUM(QUANTITY) > 0 enforced via HAVING. The system MUST NOT use AVG(unit_price).
MINIMUM BUYER COUNT GUARD (CRITICAL)
Percentile computation MUST only be performed for (product_dimension, unit_norm) pairs where COUNT(DISTINCT buyer_name_norm) >= 10 after applying all filters. Any pair failing this guard MUST be excluded entirely from all downstream CTEs including percentiles, high-margin identification, unit ranking, and final output. No fallback or relaxed threshold is permitted unless the user explicitly requests one.
PRICE OUTLIER GUARD (RECOMMENDED — OPTIONAL, P90 STABILITY)
